\section{Energy issues and solutions}

\subsection{Demand for new energy sources}

Fossil fuels (coal, oil and natural gas) have greatly influenced our lives for a long time and still play a dominate role in the current world energy consumption, as shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:energy2017}. The fossil fuels not only have a harmful effect on the environment, e.g., the air pollution and the global warming by the greenhouse gas, but also face the exhaustion problem \cite{Abas_2015_Fs}. It has been estimated that coal, oil and natural gas will be used up to about 110, 50 and 50 years, respectively \cite{Shafiee_2009_NP}. The increasing rate and types of the renewable energy \cite{Akella_2009_RE} are the sign of the rising need for cleaner and endless energy with more economic efficiency. However, those renewable energies including water, solar, wind, geothermal and biomass \cite{Fridleifsson_2001_RSER, Momirlan_2005_IJHE, Jacobson_2011_EP} are limited by the local natural conditions thus not feasible around the world \cite{Panwar_2011_RSER} as well as the storage problems \cite{Agbossou_2004_IEEE, Kaldellis_2007_En, Rentizelas_2009_RSER}.

