\subsection{Principles of fusion}

Figure \ref{fig:binding_energy} shows that the binding energy increases much faster towards the maximum energy in the moderate mass number (Fe) in the fusion region than the fission region, leading to a higher efficiency of energy generation of fusion. The basic fusion reactions with the largest cross sections are \cite{Freidberg_2007_Plasma}: %
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\begin{eqnarray}
    \mathrm{D} &+& \mathrm{T} \rightarrow \alpha + \mathrm{n} + \mathrm{17.6\ MeV}, \\
    \mathrm{D} &+& \mathrm{D} \rightarrow \mathrm{He^3} + \mathrm{n} + \mathrm{3.27\ MeV}, \\
    \mathrm{D} &+& \mathrm{D} \rightarrow \mathrm{T} + \mathrm{p} + \mathrm{4.03\ MeV}, \\
    \mathrm{D} &+& \mathrm{He^3} \rightarrow \alpha + \mathrm{p} + \mathrm{18.3\ MeV}.
\end{eqnarray}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\noindent Here, D is deuterium nucleus ($_1$H$^2$), T is tritium nucleus ($_1$H$^3$), He$^3$ is helium-3 ($_2$He$^3$), $\alpha$ is helium nucleus (alpha particle, $_2$He$^4$), n is neutron, p is proton. To realize a controlled self-sustaining burning of the fuels, the product of fuel density and energy confinement time should satisfy the ignition condition \cite{Wesson_1997_Tokamaks}:%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\begin{equation}
    n\tau_\mathrm{E}> 1.5 \times 10^{20}\ m^{-3}s.
\end{equation}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\noindent In terms of power balance, the loss power is balanced by the externally supplied power plus the $\alpha-$particle power: $P_L=P_H+P_{\alpha}$. A factor called $Q$ is a measurement of successful reactor condition:%
%%
\begin{equation}\label{eq:Q}
  Q=\frac{P_{\alpha}}{P_H},
\end{equation}
\noindent here, $Q=1$ means that 20$\%$ of the applied heating power comes from the $\alpha-$particle. At ignition, $P_H$ should be zero and $Q\rightarrow\infty$ thus all the loss power is compensated by the $\alpha-$particle power.

There are two distinct methods to approach the condition: magnetic confinement fusion (MCF) \cite{Artsimovich_1972_NF} and inertial confinement fusion (ICF) \cite{Miller_2004_NF_NIF, Craxton_2015_PoP}. MCF aims at increasing the confinement time of low-density plasmas using magnetic fields whereas ICF confines extremely high density plasmas with laser beam during a short time. ICF has been studied for instance at the National Ignition Facility (NIF) \cite{Moses_2016_FST} but the ignition condition has not been reached due to some unsolved physical problems such as controlling symmetry of the imploding fuel \cite{Michel_PRL_2009}, Rayleigh-Taylor instabilities \cite{Nagel_2017_PoP}, shockwave convergence \cite{Ma_2016_IEEE}, etc., and the $Q$ value is much lower than the expectation \cite{Ross_2015_PRE, Le-Pape_2018_PRL}. In the meantime, the ignition condition and the $Q$ value have been greatly progressed through MCF with confinement times on the order of magnitude of seconds and $Q>1$ \cite{Romanelli_2015_NF}. The essential motivation of this thesis is based on MCF, which is the most advanced fusion method.

\subsection{Plasmas}

In nuclear fusion, high temperature (typically tens of keV or tens of millions of degrees) is required to overcome the strong Coulomb repulsion. At such high temperatures, the kinetic energy per particle is much larger than its ionization energy (order of eV) so the reaction fuels no longer form neutral atoms but exist in the plasma state.

The magnetohydrodynamics (MHD) \cite{Goldston_1995_Plasma, Freidberg_2007_Plasma} and kinetic theory \cite{Stix_1992_Waves, Bittencourt_2004_Plasma} have been developed to describe the complex plasmas behaviors in space and laboratories. In MHD description, plasmas are regarded as fluid elements in electromagnetic fields; in kinetic theory, the distribution function in six-dimensional phase space is used to describe the plasma motions in a statistical view.

Intuitively, a plasma is a quasi-neutral gas of charged and neutral particles \cite{Chen_2006_Plasma} and the movements of the charged particles are mainly determined by long-range electromagnetic forces instead of short-range Coulomb collisions. In order to confine the charged particles, the external magnetic fields can be used.

\section{Tokamaks}

\subsection{Magnetic confinement and geometry}

In nuclear fusion plasmas the charged particles are confined doing gyro motions around the external magnetic field lines. Figure \ref{fig:gyro_motion} shows the helical motion of a charged particle around $\textbf{B}$ in uniform magnetic fields. With the Lorentz force $F=q_{s} \boldsymbol{\upsilon} \times \bf{B}$, the gyro radius or Larmor radius $\rho_{s}$ and the gyro frequency $\omega_{cs}$ are defined as
\begin{eqnarray}
  \rho_{s} &=& \frac{m_{s}\upsilon_{\perp}}{q_{s}B}, \\
  \omega_{cs} &=& \frac{q_{s}B}{m_{s}},
\end{eqnarray}
\noindent where $m_{s}$ is the mass, $\upsilon_{\perp}$ is the velocity perpendicular to $\textbf{B}$, $q_{s}$ is the charge, $B$ is the magnitude of the uniform magnetic fields for a particle species $s$.

%%
\begin{figure}
\begin{centering}
\includegraphics[scale=0.2]{gyro_motion.png}
\par\end{centering}
\caption[Gyro motion of charged particles in magnetic fields]{Gyro motion of charged particles in magnetic fields. The uniform magnetic fields are prescribed for simplicity. Copyright@ 2004 Pearson Education, Inc., publishing as Addison Wesley.}\label{fig:gyro_motion}
\end{figure}
%%

In a cylindrical configuration, the particles loss the confinement in the ends of the magnetic field lines due to the parallel velocity $\upsilon_{\parallel}$. So the magnetic fields should be connected end to end by bending the cylindrical configuration into a torus. Furthermore, in order to compensate the particle drifts caused by the torroidal geometry effect, the magnetic fields have to be twisted to become helical field lines. There are two methods to generate the helical magnetic fields. One straightforward way is to construct helical magnetic coils and the corresponding apparatus is called stellarator. However, the building of such magnetic coils needs extremely high accuracy and it is very complicated to guarantee the precise magnetic fields \cite{Motojima_2000_NF_LHD}. Tokamak is the other concept to realize the required magnetic configuration through large plasma currents. The confinement performance of tokamaks has been greatly improved during last decades and the International Thermonuclear Experiment Reactor (ITER) being built in southern France will become the largest tokamak in the world and will test the technical feasibility of the fusion energy.

Figure \ref{fig:magnetic_field} shows the generation of the helical magnetic fields ($B_{tot}$) through the composition of toroidal magnetic fields $B_{tor}$ and poloidal magnetic fields $B_{pol}$ in tokamaks. The toroidal and poloidal magnetic fields are generated by the external magnetic coils and the plasma current ($I_p$), respectively. In tokamaks, the toroidal plasma current is very large (order of MA) to generate proper $B_{pol}$.

%%
\begin{figure}
\begin{centering}
\includegraphics[scale=0.6]{B.png}
\par\end{centering}
\caption[Composition of the total helical magnetic fields]{Composition of the total helical magnetic fields $B_{tot}$ (c) in tokamaks from (a) toroidal $B_{\phi}$  and (b) poloidal $B_{\theta}$ magnetic fields.}\label{fig:magnetic_field}
\end{figure}
%%

The charged particles (electrons and ions) in the confined plasmas move around the torus along the helical magnetic fields. Assuming that the particles return to the previous positions after $m$ laps in the toroidal direction and $n$ laps in the poloidal direction, the \emph{safety factor} $q$ is defined as %
%%
\begin{equation}
q=\frac{m}{n},
\end{equation}
%%
\noindent which is the measurement of twist or helicity of the magnetic fields, i.e., the weaker the twist the larger the safety factor $q$.
The plasmas in tokamaks become unstable when $q$ is smaller than 1, so larger $q$ provides better stability, explaining where the name safety factor comes from.

%%
\begin{figure}
\begin{centering}
\includegraphics[scale=0.3]{cross_section.png}
\par\end{centering}
\caption[Cross-section of tokamkas]{Illustration of a simple circular cross-section of tokamaks to define the basic parameters in tokamak configurations.}\label{fig:cross_section}
\end{figure}
%%

Figure \ref{fig:cross_section} shows the cross-section of the plasmas in tokamaks, with $\phi$, $\theta$, $R$ the toroidal, poloidal and radial coordinate, respectively. The major radius of the tokamaks ($R_p$) is defined as the distance between the plasma center ($O$) and the central axis ($L_0$). In the plane of the poloidal cross-section, the plasmas positions are determined by the  polar coordinates ($r,\theta$). The helical magnetic fields form magnetic surfaces at different radial position ($r$) from the plasma center. The magnetic fields are closed within each magnetic surface except in the edge region, where the field lines are directed towards the wall.

The last closed field surface (LCFS) is the separation between the closed and open magnetic field lines. Accordingly, the minor radius of the plasmas ($a$) is defined as the radial position of the LCFS with respect to the plasma center. The inner and outer part with respect to the plasma center of the tokamak are defined as the high field side (HFS) and low field side (LFS) due to the fact that magnetic field  decreases monotonously from the central axis through the inner part to the outer part. Normally, the safety factor profiles increasing monotonously from the plasma center towards the edge and being symmetrical with respect to the plasma center, can be approximated by %
%%
\begin{equation}
q(r)=\frac{2{\pi}r^2B_{\phi}}{\mu_0I(r)R},
\end{equation}
%%
\noindent where $r$ is the radial position in the poloidal cross-section, $\mu_0$ is the space permeability, $I(r)$ is the plasma current in $r$, $R$ is the radial position in torus. So the edge safety factor ($q_{\psi}$) is given by%
%%
\begin{equation}
q_{\psi}=\frac{2{\pi}a^2B_{\phi}}{\mu_0I(a)R}.
\end{equation}
%%

The radial positions with rational numbers of the safety factor ($q=1,2,3/2,4/3,...$) are important since the MHD instabilities such as magnetic islands and tearing modes can form under certain conditions. Especially, the $q=1$ position is related to the sawteeth instabilities \cite{Chapman_2011_PPCF_ST_review}, which are periodic crash and relaxation of the core plasma temperature affecting the plasma confinement.

In slow varying magnetic fields, the magnetic moment %
%%
\begin{equation}
\mu = \frac{mv_{\perp}^2}{2B}
\end{equation}
%%
\noindent is an adiabatic invariant. So the particles with small $v_{\parallel}$ could be reflected in the region with higher magnetic fields and thus trapped in the LFS. Figure \ref{fig:trapped_particles} shows the two types of the charged particles: trapped and passing particles. The trapped particles have a trajectory whose poloidal projection is banana-shaped and the banana width is:
%%
\begin{equation}
\delta_b = \frac{2q\rho_s}{\sqrt{r/R}}.
\end{equation}
%%

%%
\begin{figure}
\begin{centering}
\includegraphics[scale=0.4]{trapped_particles.png}
\par\end{centering}
\caption[Trapped and passing particles]{Trapped and passing particles in the view of the poloidal cross-section of tokamaks.}\label{fig:trapped_particles}
\end{figure}
