\subsection{Heating scenarios}

In a self-burning D-T fusion plasma, the energy losses are balanced by the energy of the $\alpha$ particles. However, to fulfil the ignition condition or study the plasma behaviors without the $\alpha$ particles, it is necessary to provide some additional heating \cite{Wesson_1997_Tokamaks}.

The fundamental heating method is the Ohmic heating by the large toroidal plasma current through the Joule effect. The Ohmic heating density is %
%%
\begin{equation}
P_{\mathrm{Ohmic}}=\eta j^2,
\end{equation}
%%
\noindent where $\eta$ and $j$ are the plasma resistivity and current density, respectively. In Ohmic heating operation, there are two different confinement regions associated to the electron density:
\begin{itemize}

  \item At low densities, the confinement time $\tau_{E}$ increases linearly with the increase of the density in the so-called linear Ohmic confinement (LOC).
      
  \item Above a critical density threshold, the confinement time $\tau_{E}$ saturates in the so-called Ohmic confinement (SOC) regime.
      
\end{itemize}
\noindent The critical density of the LOC-SOC transition can be estimated \cite{shimomura_LOC_SOC_transition_1985}: %
%%
\begin{equation}
n_{c} \approx \frac{I_p\mu_0}{2{\pi}a^2}\sqrt{\frac{A_i\kappa}{2}},
\end{equation}
%%
\noindent where $I_p$ is the plasma current, $a$ is the minor radius, $A_i$ is the plasma atomic mass number, $\kappa$ is the plasma elongation, $\mu_0$ is the vacuum permeability. Note that $n_c$ is proportional to $I_p$ when $a$, $A_i$ and $\kappa$ keep the same. Figure \ref{fig:loc_soc_hugo} shows the LOC-SOC transition in high (1.2 MA) and low (0.5 MA) plasma current from selected Tore Supra Ohmic heating discharges.

%%
\begin{figure}
\begin{centering}
\includegraphics[scale=0.5]{loc_soc_hugo.png}
\par\end{centering}
\caption[LOC-SOC from some dedicated discharges]{The energy confinement time as a function of the central line averaged density from \cite{Arnichand_2015_Thesis}. The magnetic fields are 3.8 T for the discharges studied.}\label{fig:loc_soc_hugo}
\end{figure}
%%

The Ohmic heating is strong at low temperatures but becomes less efficient at high temperatures since $\eta$ decreases rapidly with temperature ($\eta \propto T_e^{-3/2}$). So other auxiliary heating methods are required:
\begin{itemize}

  \item \textbf{Lower-hybrid heating (LH)}: LH uses the electromagnetic waves in the frequency range 1-8 GHz. The frequencies are between the ion and electron cyclotron frequency: $\omega_{ci} < \omega < \omega_{ce}$. LH is particularly useful for current drive because of its effect on current profiles. LH is also the conventional heating methods in long-pulse discharges.

  \item \textbf{Ion cyclotron resonance heating (ICRH)}: ICRH transfers the wave energy to ions at the resonance condition $\omega=\omega_{ci}$. 

  \item \textbf{Electron cyclotron resonance heating (ECRH)}: ECRH directly heats the electrons through microwave generators in the frequency range of GHz.

  \item \textbf{Neutral beam injection (NBI)}: NBI heats both electrons and ions through the Coulomb collisions between the neutral particles and the charged particles in plasmas.

\end{itemize}

In auxiliary heated plasmas, the charged particles gain kinetic energy from the injected waves or beams and become energetic particles. LH and ECRH could generate fast electrons, which can further drive the electron fishbone instabilities. ICRH and NBI give rise to different types of instabilities such as the energetic-ion-driven Alfv\'{e}n waves. 

It was found that tokamak operations transit abruptly from low confinement mode (L-mode) to high confinement mode (H-mode) when the auxiliary heating power reaches a critical value. The underlying physics mechanisms of the L-H transition are still unclear. Some research argues the possible link between the transition and the turbulence suppression. The scaling laws of the threshold power have also been extensively investigated. The confinement time of the H-mode regime is at least twice as large compared to the L-mode regime but at the price of MHD instabilities, so-called edge localized modes (ELMs) \cite{Zohm_1996_PPCF_ELM, Connor_1998_PPCF_ELM, Howard_2008_FST, Leonard_2014_PoP_ELM}, which appears spontaneously in H-mode plasmas.

\subsection{Turbulence study}

Although great processes have been made in tokamak fusion study, one unresolved physical issue remains: plasma turbulence, which causes the large radial particle and energy loss thus degrades the confinement performance.

Turbulence is related to most of the important physical phenomena or processes in fusion plasmas. Among the different confinement regimes or heating methods mentioned, the LOC and SOC regimes might be related to turbulence driven by different micro-instabilities. In additional heating plasmas, turbulence magnitude increases in different level or channels. Turbulence suppression is also related to the L-H transitions.

Therefore, understanding plasma turbulence in tokamkas is such an significant research topic, which could help to control it and enhance the confinement performance. Motivated by this, this work took a first attempt to extract the general properties of plasma turbulence in tokamaks.

