Some basic diagnostics measures electron density $n_e$ and temperature $T_e$:
\begin{itemize}

  \item A 10-channel far-infrared interferometry system was installed to measure the electron density profiles ($n_e(r)$) with 1 ms time resolution \cite{Gil_2009_FST}. Measurements of edge density has larger uncertainties due to the lack of spatial points in the strong $\nabla n$ region. The interferometry data provide the initial edge density for the calculations of the cut-off positions from fluctuation reflectometry.

  \item A fast-sweeping X-mode reflectometry system detects the edge electron profiles with 2 $\mu$s time resolution and less than 1 cm spatial resolution. The system has 2 reflectometers, operating at V-band (50-75 GHz) and W-band (75-110 GHz) \cite{Clairet_2010_RSI}. Fast-sweeping reflectometry provides a more accurate measurement of $n_e(r)$ than interferometry but could not provide the density profiles for the fixed frequency reflectometry since the two reflectometry diagnostics are coupled in the same system on Tore Supra and cannot operate at the same time.

  \item A 32-channel electron cyclotron emission (ECE) system \cite{Segui_2005_RSI} was installed to measure the electron temperature profiles ($T_e(r)$) with both slow (1 ms) and fast (10 $\mu$s) acquisition and spatial resolution of 2 $\sim$ 3 cm. The ECE is helpful to validate the positions of the q=1 surface.

\end{itemize}


In order to carry out a systematic turbulence study, some specific turbulence diagnostics as well as diagnostics for the basic plasma parameters are necessary.

Three reflectometry diagnostics are available for turbulence study in different measurement ranges:%
\begin{enumerate}

  \item A fixed-frequency D-band (110-150 GHz) reflectometry has been installed to diagnose the core density fluctuation with high signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) \cite{Sabot_2006_NF}.

  \item A Doppler reflectometry can measure the poloidal density fluctuation with different wavenumbers and also provide the turbulence poloidal rotation velocity \cite{Hennequin_2006_NF}.

  \item A fast-sweeping refectometry system has also been used to measure the edge density fluctuation \cite{Vermare_2006_NF}.

\end{enumerate}



\section{Motivations and objectives of this thesis}

\subsection{Gradient-driven turbulence}

In tokamak fusion plasmas, the electron density ($n_e$) and temperature $T_e$ are very high in the central region to fulfil the ignition condition. The typical $n_e$ and $T_e$ are $1\times 10^{20}\ m^{-3}$ and $10\ keV$, respectively. In the edge region near the wall, $n_e$ and $T_e$ decrease to the order of $10^{17}\ m^{-3}$ and $10\ eV$, respectively, to avoid excessive heat and flux load on the wall.

%%
\begin{figure}
\begin{centering}
\includegraphics[scale=1]{gradient.png}
\par\end{centering}
\caption[Gradient from core to edge]{Strong $n_e$ and $T_e$ gradient between the central and edge region of tokamaks. }\label{fig:gradient}
\end{figure}
%%

Figure \ref{fig:gradient} illustrates the large disparity of $n_e$ and $T_e$ in the central and edge regions as well as the typical electron density profile $n_e(r)$ and temperature gradient $T_e(r)$. Then, a region with strong gradient of $n_e$, $T_e$ and plasma pressure $p$ ($p=nKT$, with $K$ the Boltzmann constant) exists between the central and edge regions. The strong gradient (directed from the core to the edge) then brings free energy in the plasma thermodynamics system. The free energy causes some micro-instabilities which can develop into the saturation state called \emph{turbulence}. Particles and energy could transfer across the turbulence vortices rapidly. Consequently, the cross-field transport increases and the confinement performance degrades.

The simplified physics process is depicted in Fig.~\ref{fig:process}. In this complex, highly nonlinear and self-regulating system, the underling mechanisms from the micro-instabilities to turbulence are still unknown although linear and nonlinear theories \cite{Diamond_ZF_2005_PPCF} have been developed. Experimentally, Many diagnostics and analysis methods have been developed to measure the fluctuations of density $\tilde{n}$, temperature $\tilde{T}$, phase $\tilde{\phi}$ and magnetic field $\tilde{B}$ originated from plasma turbulence. The relations between turbulence and transport are also unclear so far. Since turbulence has deleterious effects on the confinement, it is very significant to understand the underlying physics in the instabilities-turbulence-transport process. A comprehensive and deep understanding of the turbulence properties could help to control the turbulence and enhance the confinement performance.

%%
\begin{figure}
\begin{centering}
\includegraphics[scale=0.8]{process.png}
\par\end{centering}
\caption[Gradient-instability-turbulence-transport]{Simplified physics process of the turbulence and transport process.}\label{fig:process}
\end{figure}
%%

In general, experimental analyses of turbulence properties have concentrated on limited numbers of discharges with selected parameters. In this usual approach, only one or a few parameters are scanned, while others are kept constant. This way, analyzing trends occurring over a large range of the operational space, with multiple variables changing at the same time, is difficult.

\subsection{Objective: a systematic turbulence study}

As a complementary approach to more common studies based on the limited, well-controlled data set, this thesis proposes a systematic turbulence analysis using a large database obtained under a wide variety of plasma conditions. Database has been used to investigate some general properties in fusion plasma such as the scaling laws of the confinement time and the L-H power threshold but the application to the turbulence study has not been reported.

The data used in this thesis are the turbulence frequency spectrum inferred from density fluctuation $\tilde{n}$ measurements of fixed frequency reflectometry. The frequency spectrum from the fixed frequency reflectometry contains abundant density fluctuation information with high signal-to-noise ratio (SNR). Usually, a fluctuation frequency spectrum contains the power distribution of $\sim$ 1000 frequencies, i.e., 1000 parameters. The number of parameters in the frequency spectrum are too large to carry out a systematic study so that a parameter reduction is required.

