\end{figure}
%%

The parameter reduction relies on a decomposition of the turbulence spectrum. This decomposition method is based on the pioneering works of \cite{Vershkov_2005_NF} and \cite{Kramer-Flecken_2015_NJP}, as shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:decomposition}. In their works, the power or coherence spectra were decomposed into several components. The physical meaning of each component will be detailed in Chapter 4. Through radial, poloidal and long-range correlation, they have investigated different components of the turbulence spectrum and their properties. In this work, each component in the spectrum is fitted by a simple parameterized function, called \emph{parametrization} of spectrum.

The fluctuation parameters from parametrization are used to characterize the turbulence properties. The study focuses on Ohmic, ICRH and LH plasmas. The turbulence database then includes the fluctuation parameters together with the diagnostics and plasma parameters from other measurements.

