\section{Outline of this thesis}

In order to systematically link the properties of the fluctuation spectrum to the underlying physics in a large set of discharges under widely varying plasma conditions, it is very important to extract in a robust way the salient features from the data and describe them using a minimal set of parameters.

In this work, three different parametric models were used and their performance over the entire database was compared quantitatively. Great care was taken to obtain the optimal solution of the parametrization, taking into account the physical interpretation of the various spectrum components, with satisfactory results. The parametrization method was then applied to investigate the evolution of turbulence with respect to local and global plasma parameters in Ohmic, ICRH and LH plasmas. The following of the thesis report is organized as follows.

\begin{itemize}

  \item \textbf{Chapter 2} first introduces the origination of turbulence in tokamak fusion plasmas from the micro-instabilities, focusing on TEM and ITG instabilities. Then, the relations of the fluctuation measurement signal to the turbulence properties are discussed and the data analysis techniques of the fluctuation signal described. The effects of turbulence on transport and confinement and some important fluctuation properties are discussed.

  \item \textbf{Chapter 3} starts from the review of the classical electromagnetic waves propagation theory. The principles based on the concept of wave reflected on cut-off layer is presented. Then, the link of the fixed frequency fluctuation signal to the fluctuation properties is built. Some issues in the measurements and analysis are discussed to help interpret the fluctuation signal. The reflectometry set-up used in this thesis comes at last.

  \item \textbf{Chapter 4} is dedicated to the parametrization of the fluctuation frequency spectra, focusing on the optimization of the spectrum fitting process. Three fitting models will be compared in statistical and representative spectra.

  \item \textbf{Chapter 5} reports on the parametrization method applied to Ohmic heating plasmas. First, the radial profiles of broadband spectral component contribution are investigated. A basin structure is observed in the core region and its link to the q=1 surface  is discussed. Then, the comparisons of fluctuation properties in LOC and SOC regimes are made. Finally, a new systematic method to reconstruct the radial profiles of fluctuation level is developed.

  \item In \textbf{Chapter 6}, the method is extended to auxiliary heated plasmas including ICRH and LH scenarios. Focus has been put on explaining the different behaviors of fluctuation properties in ICRH discharges

  \item \textbf{Chapter 7} summaries the main results and conclusions of this thesis. Some pending issues and the motivation for future work will be discussed

\end{itemize}
